Reasoning: The paper discusses methods for estimating outcome probabilities for future comparisons among a collection of items, which is a common problem in machine learning and data science. The use of pairwise comparison data and the focus on adaptivity suggest that the paper may belong to the sub-category of machine learning (cs.LG). The mention of an oracle estimator and the analysis of computational efficiency suggest that the paper may also belong to the sub-category of artificial intelligence (cs.AI). The use of algorithms and the analysis of their performance suggest that the paper may belong to the sub-category of data structures and algorithms (cs.DS) or computational complexity (cs.CC). Finally, the mention of least squares estimators and the analysis of their limitations suggest that the paper may also belong to the sub-category of information theory (cs.IT).
